---
const capabilities = [
  {
    title: "Field-level allow-lists",
    body:
      "Whitelist what's relevant. The rest never leaves your tool's boundary.",
  },
  {
    title: "PII masking and redaction",
    body:
      "Sensitive fields can be hashed, masked, or removed before reaching the model.",
  },
  {
    title: "Metadata stripping",
    body:
      "Audit columns, internal IDs, and timestamps are dropped by default.",
  },
  {
    title: "Read-only mode per connector",
    body:
      "Block write actions entirely. Useful for pilots and compliance reviews.",
  },
  {
    title: "Tenant-isolated cache with TTL",
    body:
      "Redis-backed, namespaced per tenant, never persisted to disk. TTLs bounded by policy.",
  },
  {
    title: "Self-hosted or EU-hosted",
    body:
      "Helm chart for your own infra; Plynf Cloud runs in Germany. You decide where your data is.",
  },
];
---

<section class="section" id="security">
  <div class="container-page" data-reveal>
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <p class="section-eyebrow">Data minimization, not promises</p>
      <h2 class="section-title text-balance">
        The agent never sees the data it doesn't need.
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-6 text-ink-secondary text-lg leading-relaxed">
        That's not just a cost thing. It's a data-exposure thing. When you
        ship 200 Salesforce fields into an LLM call, you've effectively
        shared those fields with the model provider. Plynf lets you draw
        the line technically — which fields cross, which don't, which get
        masked, which get logged.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
      {capabilities.map((c) => (
        <div class="card p-6 h-full">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <svg class="mt-0.5 h-4 w-4 flex-none text-accent" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
              <path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4"></path>
              <path d="M12 22s8-4 8-10V5l-8-3-8 3v7c0 6 8 10 8 10z"></path>
            </svg>
            <div>
              <p class="font-medium text-ink-primary">{c.title}</p>
              <p class="mt-1.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-secondary">{c.body}</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <p class="mt-10 max-w-3xl text-2xs font-mono text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
      Plynf is a technical layer. It helps you implement data minimization,
      field-level access control, and audit logging — it does not replace a
      GDPR assessment, a DPIA, or your own legal review. DPA available on request.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
